{"version":1,"ops":[{"type":1,"author":{"id":"86141a663c2eb7543d1a51ec6253a1d54de912fd"},"timestamp":1413136540,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWU0NTU4NzkyNg==","github-url":"https://github.com/parrot/parrot/issues/1098","origin":"github"},"title":"Convert single-byte strings to ascii/latin1 if the default platform encoding is multibyte","message":"On linux and now also on BSD's (including darwin) the default platform encoding is mostly utf-8.\nThis is needed to print strings in utf8 terminals.\nBut that means lots of previously ascii strings taken not from pir/pbc/pasm but from ENV and the cmdline, are now all treated as utf8, thus using slower ord, substr, ...\n\nWe should scan those external strings for pure-ascii and set the ascii encoding if the multibyte platform encoding is not needed. This is mostly helpful to Getopt handling.\nWe cannot set latin1 as this is incompatible to utf-8.","files":null}]}